# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bonferroni-correction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] Statistical hypothesis testing is based on rejecting the null hypothesis when the likelihood of the observed data would be low if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] When multiple hypotheses are tested, the probability of observing a rare event increases, so the likelihood of incorrectly rejecting a null hypothesis (i.e., making a Type I error) increases if multiple null hypotheses are true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] The Bonferroni correction compensates for that increase by testing each individual hypothesis at a significance level of $\alpha /m$ , where $\alpha$ is the desired overall alpha level and m is the number of hypotheses.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] For example, if a trial is testing $m=20$ hypotheses with a desired overall $\alpha =0.05$ , the Bonferroni-corrected alpha level would be $\alpha =0.05/20=0.0025$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] The method is named for its use of the Bonferroni inequalities.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] The Bonferroni correction can also be applied as a p-value adjustment: Using that approach, instead of adjusting the alpha level, each p-value is multiplied by the number of tests (with adjusted p-values that exceed 1 then being reduced to 1), and the alpha level is left unchanged.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] The significance decisions using this approach will be the same as when using the alpha-level adjustment approach.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] Let $H_{1},\ldots ,H_{m}$ be a family of null hypotheses and let $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{m}$ be their corresponding p-values.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] Let m be the total number of null hypotheses, and let $m_{0}$ be the number of true null hypotheses (which is presumably unknown to the researcher).
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] The family-wise error rate (FWER) is the probability of rejecting at least one true $H_{i}$ , that is, of making at least one type I error.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] The Bonferroni correction rejects the null hypothesis for each $p_{i}\leq {\frac {\alpha }{m}}$ , thereby controlling the FWER at $\leq \alpha$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] This control does not require any assumptions about dependence among the p-values or about how many of the null hypotheses are true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] Rather than testing each hypothesis at the $\alpha /m$ level, the hypotheses may be tested at any other combination of levels that add up to $\alpha$ , provided that the level of each test is decided before looking at the data.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] For example, for two hypothesis tests, an overall $\alpha$ of 0.05 could be maintained by conducting one test at 0.04 and the other at 0.01.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] The procedure proposed by Dunn can be used to adjust confidence intervals.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] If one establishes m confidence intervals, and wishes to have an overall confidence level of $1-\alpha$ , each individual confidence interval can be adjusted to the level of $1-{\frac {\alpha }{m}}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] When searching for a signal in a continuous parameter space there can also be a problem of multiple comparisons, or look-elsewhere effect.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] For example, a physicist might be looking to discover a particle of unknown mass by considering a large range of masses; this was the case during the Nobel Prize winning detection of the Higgs boson.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] In such cases, one can apply a continuous generalization of the Bonferroni correction by employing Bayesian logic to relate the effective number of trials, m , to the prior-to-posterior volume ratio.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] There are alternative ways to control the family-wise error rate.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] For example, the Holm–Bonferroni method and the Šidák correction are universally more powerful procedures than the Bonferroni correction, meaning that they are always at least as powerful.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] But unlike the Bonferroni procedure, these methods do not control the expected number of Type I errors per family (the per-family Type I error rate).
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] With respect to Family-wise error rate (FWER) control, the Bonferroni correction can be conservative if there are a large number of tests and/or the test statistics are positively correlated, due to looseness of the union bound for significantly overlapping sets.
[src:bonferroni-correction/bonferroni-correction] Multiple-testing corrections, including the Bonferroni procedure, increase the probability of Type II errors when null hypotheses are false, i.e., they reduce statistical power.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] John Tukey developed in 1953 the concept of a familywise error rate as the probability of making a Type I error among a specified group, or "family," of tests.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Ryan (1959) proposed the related concept of an *experimentwise error rate*, which is the probability of making a Type I error in a given experiment.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Hence, an experimentwise error rate is a familywise error rate where the family includes all the tests that are conducted within an experiment.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] As Ryan (1959, Footnote 3) explained, an experiment may contain two or more families of multiple comparisons, each of which relates to a particular statistical inference and each of which has its own separate familywise error rate.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Hence, familywise error rates are usually based on theoretically informative collections of multiple comparisons.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] In contrast, an experimentwise error rate may be based on a collection of simultaneous comparisons that refer to a diverse range of separate inferences.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Some have argued that it may not be useful to control the experimentwise error rate in such cases.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Indeed, Tukey suggested that familywise control was preferable in such cases (Tukey, 1956, personal communication, in Ryan, 1962, p.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The following table defines the possible outcomes when testing multiple null hypotheses.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Suppose we have a number *m* of null hypotheses, denoted by: *H*1, *H*2, ..., *H**m*.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Using a statistical test, we reject the null hypothesis if the test is declared significant.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] We do not reject the null hypothesis if the test is non-significant.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] In m hypothesis tests of which $m_{0}$ are true null hypotheses, R is an observable random variable, and S, T, U, and V are unobservable random variables.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Thus, by assuring $\mathrm {FWER} \leq \alpha \,\!\,$ , the probability of making one or more type I errors in the family is controlled at level $\alpha \,\!$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] A procedure controls the FWER *in the weak sense* if the FWER control at level $\alpha \,\!$ is guaranteed *only* when all null hypotheses are true (i.e. when $m_{0}=m$ , meaning the "global null hypothesis" is true).
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] A procedure controls the FWER *in the strong sense* if the FWER control at level $\alpha \,\!$ is guaranteed for *any* configuration of true and non-true null hypotheses (whether the global null hypothesis is true or not).
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Some classical solutions that ensure strong level $\alpha$ FWER control, and some newer solutions exist.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] This procedure is uniformly more powerful than the Bonferroni procedure.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The reason why this procedure controls the family-wise error rate for all the m hypotheses at level α in the strong sense is, because it is a closed testing procedure.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] As such, each intersection is tested using the simple Bonferroni test.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Hochberg's procedure is more powerful than Holm's.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Nevertheless, while Holm’s is a closed testing procedure (and thus, like Bonferroni, has no restriction on the joint distribution of the test statistics), Hochberg’s is based on the Simes test, so it holds only under non-negative dependence.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The Simes test is derived under assumption of independent tests; it is conservative for tests that are positively dependent in a certain sense and is anti-conservative for certain cases of negative dependence.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] However, it has been suggested that a modified version of the Hochberg procedure remains valid under general negative dependence.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Charles Dunnett (1955, 1966) described an alternative alpha error adjustment when *k* groups are compared to the same control group.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Now known as Dunnett's test, this method is less conservative than the Bonferroni adjustment.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The procedures of Bonferroni and Holm control the FWER under any dependence structure of the *p*-values (or equivalently the individual test statistics).
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Essentially, this is achieved by accommodating a `worst-case' dependence structure (which is close to independence for most practical purposes).
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] But such an approach is conservative if dependence is actually positive.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] To give an extreme example, under perfect positive dependence, there is effectively only one test and thus, the FWER is uninflated.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Accounting for the dependence structure of the *p*-values (or of the individual test statistics) produces more powerful procedures.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] This can be achieved by applying resampling methods, such as bootstrapping and permutations methods.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The procedure of Westfall and Young (1993) requires a certain condition that does not always hold in practice (namely, subset pivotality).
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The procedures of Romano and Wolf (2005a,b) dispense with this condition and are thus more generally valid.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The harmonic mean *p*-value (HMP) procedure provides a multilevel test that improves on the power of Bonferroni correction by assessing the significance of *groups* of hypotheses while controlling the strong-sense family-wise error rate.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] This approximation is reasonable for small ${\textstyle \alpha }$ (e.g. ${\textstyle \alpha <0.05}$ ) and becomes arbitrarily good as ${\textstyle \alpha }$ approaches zero.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] An asymptotically exact test is also available (see main article).
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] FWER control exerts a more stringent control over false discovery compared to false discovery rate (FDR) procedures.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] FWER control limits the probability of *at least one* false discovery, whereas FDR control limits (in a loose sense) the expected proportion of false discoveries.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Thus, FDR procedures have greater power at the cost of increased rates of type I errors, i.e., rejecting null hypotheses that are actually true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] On the other hand, FWER control is less stringent than per-family error rate control, which limits the expected number of errors per family.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] Because FWER control is concerned with *at least one* false discovery, unlike per-family error rate control it does not treat multiple simultaneous false discoveries as any worse than one false discovery.
[src:bonferroni-correction/family-wise-error-rate] The Bonferroni correction is often considered as merely controlling the FWER, but in fact also controls the per-family error rate.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] In statistics, the **Holm–Bonferroni method**, also called the **Holm method** or **Bonferroni–Holm method**, is used to counteract the problem of multiple comparisons.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] It is intended to control the family-wise error rate (FWER) and offers a simple test uniformly more powerful than the Bonferroni correction.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] It is named after Sture Holm, who codified the method, and Carlo Emilio Bonferroni.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] When considering several hypotheses, the problem of multiplicity arises: the more hypotheses are tested, the higher the probability of obtaining Type I errors (false positives).
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The Holm–Bonferroni method is one of many approaches for controlling the FWER, i.e., the probability that one or more Type I errors will occur, by adjusting the rejection criterion for each of the individual hypotheses.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] This method ensures that the FWER is at most $\alpha$ , in the strong sense.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The simple Bonferroni correction rejects only null hypotheses with *p*-value less than or equal to ${\frac {\alpha }{m}}$ , in order to ensure that the FWER, i.e., the risk of rejecting one or more true null hypotheses (i.e., of committing one or more type I errors) is at most $\alpha$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The cost of this protection against type I errors is an increased risk of failing to reject one or more false null hypotheses (i.e., of committing one or more type II errors).
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The Holm–Bonferroni method also controls the FWER at $\alpha$ , but with a lower increase of type II error risk than the classical Bonferroni method.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The Holm–Bonferroni method sorts the *p*-values from lowest to highest and compares them to nominal alpha levels of ${\frac {\alpha }{m}}$ to $\alpha$ (respectively), namely the values ${\frac {\alpha }{m}},{\frac {\alpha }{m-1}},\ldots ,{\frac {\alpha }{2}},{\frac {\alpha }{1}}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Let $I_{0}$ be the set of indices corresponding to the (unknown) true null hypotheses, having $m_{0}$ members.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Therefore, the probability to reject a true hypothesis is at most $\alpha$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The Holm–Bonferroni method can be viewed as a closed testing procedure, with the Bonferroni correction applied locally on each of the intersections of null hypotheses.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The closure principle states that a hypothesis $H_{i}$ in a family of hypotheses $H_{1},\ldots ,H_{m}$ is rejected – while controlling the FWER at level $\alpha$ – if and only if all the sub-families of the intersections with $H_{i}$ are rejected at level $\alpha$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The Holm–Bonferroni method is a *shortcut procedure*, since it makes m or less comparisons, while the number of all intersections of null hypotheses to be tested is of order $2^{m}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] It controls the FWER in the strong sense.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] In the Holm–Bonferroni procedure, we first test $H_{(1)}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] If $H_{(1)}$ is rejected at level $\alpha /m$ then all the intersection sub-families that contain it are rejected too, thus $H_{(1)}$ is rejected.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] This is because $P_{(1)}$ is the smallest in each one of the intersection sub-families and the size of the sub-families is at most m , such that the Bonferroni threshold larger than $\alpha /m$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The same rationale applies for $H_{(2)}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] However, since $H_{(1)}$ already rejected, it sufficient to reject all the intersection sub-families of $H_{(2)}$ without $H_{(1)}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Once $P_{(2)}\leq \alpha /(m-1)$ holds all the intersections that contains $H_{(2)}$ are rejected.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The same applies for each $1\leq i\leq m$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The p-value is compared to $\alpha /4=0.0125$ , the null hypothesis is rejected and we continue to the next one.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] We stop testing and conclude that $H_{1}$ and $H_{4}$ are rejected and $H_{2}$ and $H_{3}$ are not rejected while controlling the family-wise error rate at level $\alpha =0.05$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] This is because the testing procedure stops once a failure to reject occurs.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] resulting in a slightly more powerful test.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Let $P_{(1)},\ldots ,P_{(m)}$ be the ordered unadjusted p-values.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Due to the inequality $1-(1-\alpha )^{1/n}<\alpha /n$ for $n\geq 2$ , the Holm-Šidák method will be more powerful than Holm–Bonferroni method.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] A hypothesis is rejected at level α if and only if its adjusted *p*-value is less than α.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] In the earlier example using equal weights, the adjusted *p*-values are 0.03, 0.06, 0.06, and 0.02.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] This is another way to see that using α = 0.05, only hypotheses one and four are rejected by this procedure.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] The Holm–Bonferroni method is "uniformly" more powerful than the classic Bonferroni correction, meaning that it is always at least as powerful.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] There are other methods for controlling the FWER that are more powerful than Holm–Bonferroni.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] For instance, in the Hochberg procedure, rejection of $H_{(1)}\ldots H_{(k)}$ is made after finding the *maximal* index k such that $P_{(k)}\leq {\frac {\alpha }{m+1-k}}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Thus, The Hochberg procedure is uniformly more powerful than the Holm procedure.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] However, the Hochberg procedure requires the hypotheses to be independent or under certain forms of positive dependence, whereas Holm–Bonferroni can be applied without such assumptions.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] A similar step-up procedure is the Hommel procedure, which is uniformly more powerful than the Hochberg procedure.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Carlo Emilio Bonferroni did not take part in inventing the method described here.
[src:bonferroni-correction/holm-bonferroni-method] Holm originally called the method the "sequentially rejective Bonferroni test", and it became known as Holm–Bonferroni only after some time.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The probability of false positives is measured through the family-wise error rate (FWER).
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The larger the number of inferences made in a series of tests, the more likely erroneous inferences become.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Several statistical techniques have been developed to compensate for the number of inferences being made—for example, by requiring a stricter significance threshold for individual comparisons.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The problem of multiple comparisons received increased attention in the 1950s with the work of statisticians such as Tukey and Scheffé.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Over the ensuing decades, many procedures were developed to address the problem.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] In 1996, the first international conference on multiple comparison procedures took place in Tel Aviv.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Several researchers are active in this area, for example Emmanuel Candès and Vladimir Vovk.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Multiple comparisons arise when a statistical analysis involves multiple simultaneous statistical tests, each of which has a potential to produce a "discovery".
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] A stated confidence level generally applies only to each test considered individually, but often it is desirable to have a confidence level for the whole family of simultaneous tests.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] In both examples, as the number of comparisons increases, it becomes more likely that the groups being compared will appear to differ in terms of at least one attribute.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Our confidence that a result will generalize to independent data should generally be weaker if it is observed as part of an analysis that involves multiple comparisons, rather than an analysis that involves only a single comparison.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] For example, if one test is performed at the 5% level and the corresponding null hypothesis is true, there is only a 5% risk of incorrectly rejecting the null hypothesis.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] However, if 100 tests are each conducted at the 5% level and all corresponding null hypotheses are true, the expected number of incorrect rejections (also known as false positives or Type I errors) is 5.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] If the tests are statistically independent from each other (i.e. are performed on independent samples), the probability of at least one incorrect rejection is approximately 99.4%.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The multiple comparisons problem also applies to confidence intervals.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] A single confidence interval with a 95% coverage probability level will contain the true value of the parameter in 95% of samples.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] However, if one considers 100 confidence intervals simultaneously, each with 95% coverage probability, the expected number of non-covering intervals is 5.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] If the intervals are statistically independent from each other, the probability that at least one interval does not contain the population parameter is 99.4%.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Techniques have been developed to prevent the inflation of false positive rates and non-coverage rates that occur with multiple statistical tests.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Hence, unless the tests are perfectly positively dependent (i.e., identical), ${\bar {\alpha }}$ increases as the number of comparisons increases.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] There are different ways to assure that the family-wise error rate is at most $\alpha$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The most conservative method, which is free of dependence and distributional assumptions, is the Bonferroni correction $\alpha _{\mathrm {\{per\ comparison\}} }={\alpha }/m$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] A marginally less conservative correction can be obtained by solving the equation for the family-wise error rate of m independent comparisons for $\alpha _{\mathrm {\{per\ comparison\}} }$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The classical Bonferroni method is easy to understand but should not be used since it is overly conservative.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] There are online calculators to correct for multiple comparisons using the more modern Holm-Bonferroni method or the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] For continuous problems, one can employ Bayesian logic to compute m from the prior-to-posterior volume ratio.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Continuous generalizations of the Bonferroni and Šidák correction are presented in.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Traditional methods for multiple comparisons adjustments focus on correcting for modest numbers of comparisons, often in an analysis of variance.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] A different set of techniques have been developed for "large-scale multiple testing", in which thousands or even greater numbers of tests are performed.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] For example, in genomics, when using technologies such as microarrays, expression levels of tens of thousands of genes can be measured, and genotypes for millions of genetic markers can be measured.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Particularly in the field of genetic association studies, there has been a serious problem with non-replication — a result being strongly statistically significant in one study but failing to be replicated in a follow-up study.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Such non-replication can have many causes, but it is widely considered that failure to fully account for the consequences of making multiple comparisons is one of the causes.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] It has been argued that advances in measurement and information technology have made it far easier to generate large datasets for exploratory analysis, often leading to the testing of large numbers of hypotheses with no prior basis for expecting many of the hypotheses to be true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] In this situation, very high false positive rates are expected unless multiple comparisons adjustments are made.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] For large-scale testing problems where the goal is to provide definitive results, the family-wise error rate remains the most accepted parameter for ascribing significance levels to statistical tests.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Alternatively, if a study is viewed as exploratory, or if significant results can be easily re-tested in an independent study, control of the false discovery rate (FDR) is often preferred.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The FDR, loosely defined as the expected proportion of false positives among all significant tests, allows researchers to identify a set of "candidate positives" that can be more rigorously evaluated in a follow-up study.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] The practice of trying many unadjusted comparisons in the hope of finding a significant one is a known problem, whether applied unintentionally or deliberately, is sometimes called "p-hacking".
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] A basic question faced at the outset of analyzing a large set of testing results is whether there is evidence that any of the alternative hypotheses are true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] One simple meta-test that can be applied when it is assumed that the tests are independent of each other is to use the Poisson distribution as a model for the number of significant results at a given level α that would be found when all null hypotheses are true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] If the observed number of positives is substantially greater than what should be expected, this suggests that there are likely to be some true positives among the significant results.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] For example, if 1000 independent tests are performed, each at level α = 0.05, we expect 0.05 × 1000 = 50 significant tests to occur when all null hypotheses are true.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Based on the Poisson distribution with mean 50, the probability of observing more than 61 significant tests is less than 0.05, so if more than 61 significant results are observed, it is very likely that some of them correspond to situations where the alternative hypothesis holds.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] A drawback of this approach is that it overstates the evidence that some of the alternative hypotheses are true when the test statistics are positively correlated, which commonly occurs in practice. .
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] On the other hand, the approach remains valid even in the presence of correlation among the test statistics, as long as the Poisson distribution can be shown to provide a good approximation for the number of significant results.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] This scenario arises, for instance, when mining significant frequent itemsets from transactional datasets.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Furthermore, a careful two stage analysis can bound the FDR at a pre-specified level.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] Another common approach that can be used in situations where the test statistics can be standardized to Z-scores is to make a normal quantile plot of the test statistics.
[src:bonferroni-correction/multiple-comparisons-problem] If the observed quantiles are markedly more dispersed than the normal quantiles, this suggests that some of the significant results may be true positives.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] In probability theory, **Boole's inequality**, also known as the **union bound**, says that for any finite or countable set of events, the probability that at least one of the events happens is no greater than the sum of the probabilities of the individual events.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] This inequality provides an upper bound on the probability of occurrence of at least one of a countable number of events in terms of the individual probabilities of the events.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Boole's inequality is named for its discoverer, George Boole.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] In measure-theoretic terms, Boole's inequality follows from the fact that a measure (and certainly any probability measure) is *σ*-sub-additive.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Thus Boole's inequality holds not only for probability measures ${\mathbb {P} }$ , but more generally when ${\mathbb {P} }$ is replaced by any measure.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Boole's inequality may be proved for finite collections of n events using the method of induction.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Let events $A_{1},A_{2},A_{3},\dots$ in our probability space be given.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] For the other inclusion, let $x\in \bigcup _{i=1}^{\infty }A_{i}$ be given.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Write k for the minimum positive integer such that $x\in A_{k}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] where the last inequality holds because $B_{i}\subset A_{i}$ implies that $\mathbb {P} (B_{i})\leq \mathbb {P} (A_{i}),$ for all i.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Boole's inequality for a finite number of events may be generalized to certain upper and lower bounds on the probability of finite unions of events.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] These bounds are known as **Bonferroni inequalities**, after Carlo Emilio Bonferroni; see Bonferroni (1936).
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] The inequalities follow from the inclusion–exclusion principle, and Boole's inequality is the special case of $K=1$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Since the proof of the inclusion-exclusion principle requires only the finite additivity (and nonnegativity) of $\mathbb {P}$ , the Bonferroni inequalities holds more generally when $\mathbb {P}$ is replaced by any finite content, in the sense of measure theory.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] These such E partition the sample space, and for each E and every i , E is either contained in $A_{i}$ or disjoint from it.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] If $E=\bigcap _{i=1}^{n}A_{i}^{c}$ , then E contributes 0 to both sides of the inequality.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Otherwise, assume E is contained in exactly L of the $A_{i}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] The proof for even K is nearly identical.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Suppose that you are estimating five parameters based on a random sample, and you can control each parameter separately.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] If you want your estimations of all five parameters to be good with a chance 95%, what should you do to each parameter?
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] Tuning each parameter's chance to be good to within 95% is not enough because "all are good" is a subset of each event "Estimate *i* is good".
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] We can use Boole's Inequality to solve this problem.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] One way is to make each of them equal to 0.05/5 = 0.01, that is 1%.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] In other words, you have to guarantee each estimate good to 99%( for example, by constructing a 99% confidence interval) to make sure the total estimation to be good with a chance 95%.
[src:bonferroni-correction/union-bound] This is called the Bonferroni Method of simultaneous inference.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] In statistics, the **Šidák correction**, or **Dunn–Šidák correction**, is a method used to counteract the problem of multiple comparisons.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] It is a simple method to control the family-wise error rate.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] When all null hypotheses are true, the method provides familywise error control that is exact for tests that are stochastically independent, conservative for tests that are positively dependent, and liberal for tests that are negatively dependent.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] It is credited to a 1967 paper by the statistician and probabilist Zbyněk Šidák.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] The Šidák method can be used to adjust alpha levels, p-values, or confidence intervals.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] Though slightly less conservative than Bonferroni, it tends to be a more conservative method of familywise error control compared to many other methods, especially when tests are positively dependent.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] The Šidák correction is derived by assuming that the individual tests are independent.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] Let the significance threshold for each test be $\alpha _{1}$ ; then the probability that at least one of the tests is significant under this threshold is (1 - the probability that none of them are significant).
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] Since it is assumed that they are independent, the probability that all of them are not significant is the product of the probability that each of them is not significant, or $1-(1-\alpha _{1})^{m}$ .
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] Our intention is for this probability to equal $\alpha$ , the significance threshold for the entire series of tests.
[src:bonferroni-correction/šidák-correction] By solving for $\alpha _{1}$ , we obtain $\alpha _{1}=1-(1-\alpha )^{1/m}.$ It shows that in order to reach a given $\alpha$ level, we need to adapt the $\alpha _{1}$ values used for each test.
